abstract.text: Evaluate return values that most GSS-API functions use to indicate the outcome of an operation.

inlineContent.text: The functions of the GSS-API return two status codes. The major status code, delivered as the function’s return value, provides a mechanism-independent status output. A value of

typically indicates success, but the code is actually composed of several fields that enable communicating a more nuanced result.  Always check the major status code to determine if an operation succeeds.
The minor status code provides additional information, often mechanism-specific, when an operation fails. This result returns using the

pointer given as the function’s first argument. Examine this value to further debug a problem. For example, many functions allocate memory as a side effect of their main task. If memory allocation fails, the entire operation fails. But while the major status indicates a generic problem, a minor status of
indicates that failed memory allocation is the exact culprit.

A generic GSS-API error in the most significant 8 bits.
An error specific to the routine in the next 8 bits.
Additional information about the error in the lower 16 bits.

abstract.text: Returns an error object based on GSS-API major and minor status codes.
A macro that masks out all but the calling error field from a major status code.
A mask with a width that matches the calling error field.
The offset of the calling error field within the major status code.
A flag that indicates the named status code comes from a GSS-API call.
A flag that indicates the status code comes from a call to an underlying mechanism, such as Kerberos.
A mask with a width that matches the routine error field.
The offset of the routine error field within the major status code.
A mask with a width that matches the supplementary information field.
The offset of the supplementary information field within the major status code.
A macro that masks the supplementary info out of a major status code, leaving both calling and routine error fields.
A macro that masks out all but the routine error field from a major status code.
A macro that masks out all but the supplementary information field from a major status code.
A required input parameter could not be read.
A required output parameter failed to write.
A request for continuation during context establishment.
The detection of a duplicate per-message token.
The detection of a skipped predecessor token.
The detection of a timed-out per-message token.
The detection of a reordered (early) per-message token.
